04403nam a22007095i 9780813585321DE-B159720210107041344.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210107t20172017nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2016015543  a97808135853217 a10.36019/97808135853212doi  a(DE-B1597)526336  a(OCoLC)971891535  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHE8700.72.U6 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a384.55509731 aMcMurria, John, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aRepublic on the Wire :bCable Television, Pluralism, and the Politics of New Technologies, 1948-1984 /cJohn McMurria. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 figure, 8 photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: American Pluralism, Television Policy, and the Method of Equality -- t1. Broadcast Policy, Television Spectrum, and the Pluralist Logics of Inequality -- t2. Contesting (In)Equality at the Margins of Television Reception -- t3. Pay-TV Orders -- t4. Local Origination, Public Access, and the Hierarchical Logics of Civic Culture -- t5. Blue Skies, Black Cultures -- tEpilogue: Neutrality, Connectivity, or Equality When Media Converge -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe history of cable television in America is far older than networks like MTV, ESPN, and HBO, which are so familiar to us today. Tracing the origins of cable TV back to the late 1940s, media scholar John McMurria also locates the roots of many current debates about premium television, cultural elitism, minority programming, content restriction, and corporate ownership. Republic on the Wire takes us back to the pivotal years in which media regulators and members of the viewing public presciently weighed the potential benefits and risks of a two-tiered television system, split between free broadcasts and pay cable service. Digging into rare archives, McMurria reconstructs the arguments of policymakers, whose often sincere advocacy for the public benefits of cable television were fueled by cultural elitism and the priority to maintain order during a period of urban Black rebellions. He also tells the story of the people of color, rural residents, women’s groups, veterans, seniors, and low-income viewers who challenged this reasoning and demanded an equal say over the future of television. By excavating this early cable history, and placing equality at the center of our understanding of media democracy, Republic on the Wire is a real eye-opener as it develops a new methodology for studying media policy in the past and present.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Jan 2021) 0aBroadcastingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCable televisionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aTelevision broadcastingzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package 2017z978311066609040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081358532140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813585321423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813585321.jpg  a978-3-11-066609-0  RUP eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK